Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /falˈsi.fi.koː/, [faɫ̪ˈsɪ.fɪ.koː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /falˈsi.fi.ko/, [falˈsiː.fi.kɔ]

Etymology 1[edit]

From falsus (“deceived, mistaken, false”) + faciō (“make, do”).

Verb[edit]

falsificō (present infinitive falsificāre, perfect active falsificāvī, supine falsificātum); first conjugation

  1. (Late Latin) I make false, corrupt, counterfeit; falsify

Etymology 2[edit]

Inflected form of falsificus.

Adjective[edit]

falsificō

  1. dative masculine singular of falsificus
  2. dative neuter singular of falsificus
  3. ablative masculine singular of falsificus
  4. ablative neuter singular of falsificus
